</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[189,1399,950,1082]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">
<taxonomicName authority="Sreedevi &amp; Ranasinghe &amp; Fabrizi &amp; Ahrens, 2019" authorityName="Sreedevi &amp; Ranasinghe &amp; Fabrizi &amp; Ahrens" authorityYear="2019" box="[189,398,951,976]" class="Insecta" family="Melolonthidae" genus="Neoserica" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="reuteri" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[189,398,951,976]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Neoserica reuteri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[409,503,951,977]" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is in its external appearance very similar to the species of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Moser" authorityYear="1908" class="Insecta" family="Melolonthidae" genus="Neoserica" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="16" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="abnormis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="16">Neoserica abnormis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group. It differs from most similar Southern Indian taxa by the smaller body size, the bicolored body surface and the subsymmetrical genitalia (rather than evidently asymmetrical in other species): the apex of the phallobase and the tip of the parameres are slightly asymmetrical.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
